# CONCENTRATION RISKS

- **Primary concentration: NVDA and TSM are the demand anchor and production floor for the entire causal chain** — If hyperscaler CapEx decelerates, both positions fall together and there is no diversification benefit from LITE, AVGO, SMH, or QQQ because they are all downstream of the same demand shock.
- **Secondary concentration: LITE and AVGO are frontier bets priced on adoption that has not yet generated binding orders** — These positions have no independent demand signal; they are pure leveraged bets on the NVDA/TSM thesis, which means they amplify drawdown risk by 30–40% in a correction.
- **Simultaneous drawdown trigger: hyperscaler CapEx repriorization from "growth" to "efficiency"** — If this happens, NVDA, TSM, LITE, and AVGO all fall 15–30% within 4–8 weeks; SMH and QQQ provide no cushion because they are correlated to the same demand shock; only G3B.SI might provide diversification, but the thesis is unproven in a crisis.

---

# ONE THING TO WATCH

- **The single most important signal: hyperscaler CapEx intensity (CapEx as % of revenue) in next earnings cycle** — This number tells you whether CapEx growth is accelerating (thesis intact) or decelerating (thesis broken); if intensity is falling YoY, custom silicon adoption and optical interconnects are cost-optimization signals, not growth signals.
- **Where to look: Microsoft, Google, Meta, Amazon earnings calls (expected late July for Q2 2026 results)** — Listen for management language shift from "growth CapEx" to "efficiency CapEx"; watch for CapEx guidance growth rates <15% YoY; note any delays or cancellations in custom chip or optical interconnect programs.
- **Weekly premortem running: if this thesis is wrong in 12 months, what killed it?** — The portfolio is pricing a hyperscaler AI CapEx acceleration that may have already peaked; if hyperscaler CapEx is rolling over from 40% YoY growth into 15–20% YoY growth, the portfolio experiences a 15–25% drawdown over 8–12 weeks as institutions rotate out of concentrated positions (NVDA, TSM) into lower-conviction holdings (LITE, secondary semiconductors), and LITE/AVGO experience 30–40% declines due to visibility collapse; regulatory fragmentation (energy policy, export controls, MAS tightening) is the mechanism that triggers this repriorization, not a tail risk.